Results
:::

::: {style="font-size:35px"}
Now we estimate Coubb-Duglas cost function coefficients using panel data linear regression

::: columns
::: {.column width="70%"}

::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```

==================================================
                           Dependent variable:    
                       ---------------------------
                             ln(Total Cost)       
--------------------------------------------------
ln(Price of Labor)          0.404*** (0.044)      
ln(Price of Utilities)      0.244*** (0.055)      
ln(Price of Capital)        0.241*** (0.030)      
ln(Output)                    0.085 (0.051)       
--------------------------------------------------
Observations                       143            
R2                                0.832           
Adjusted R2                       0.821           
F Statistic             164.734*** (df = 4; 133)  
==================================================
Note:                  *p<0.1; **p<0.05; ***p<0.01
```
:::
:::

:::

::: {.column width="30%"}
As we can see, all coefficients sum to 1, but this has to be checked
:::

:::

:::

::: {.footer style="height:55px;background-color:lightgray;z-index:-1;bottom:0%"}
::: footer
